in terminal:
$ uv tool install specify-cli --from git+https://github.com/github/spec-kit.git@v0.12.1
$ specify init spec-kit-practice --integration copilot
$ cd spec-kit-practice 
$ specify version   

open a project in VScode, open terminal there (cmd+J)
$ uvx --from git+https://github.com/github/spec-kit.git specify init --here
then follow the prompts to finish applying spec-kit with copilot
by now there would be an extra folder called '.github' pulled to the project

/constitution -> /specify -> /plan -> /tasks -> /implement                  //newer version would be /speckit.constitution  /speckit.specify  etc. 
/constitution doesnt need to be run every time as it is project-level governing principles.
optional commands would be /clarify which is following /specify, and /analyze which is following /tasks

how this workflow works:
step 1:
input and run /constitution blablablabla~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
when we run /consitituion, it fires the constitution prompts, which tells the coding agent to fill in .specify/memory/constitution.md by extracting any input we give it
and using that to fill in any placeholder tokens. 
step 2:
/specify (should focus on what and why instead of how)
speckit.specify.agent.md: defines how AI fills in the content of spec.md
.specify/scripts/bash/create-new-feature.sh: creates a new feature folder under /spec based on feature description, and generates spec.md.
running /specify also creates a new branch
input and run /specify <branch name> - blablablabla~~~~~~~~~~~~~~           
it would generate specs/001-<branch name>/spec.md under ./specify, spec.md inlcudes user stories, acceptance criteria, functional requriements etc.
the way of naming the feature is defined in create-new-feature.sh under /scripts/bash
step 2.1:
/clarify
just run /clarify, it would go through spec.md, and ask more questions which need replies to be provided 
step 3:
/plan <outline any technical implementation details like framework, library, third party service etc.>
in speckit.plan.agent.md it defines how this step works
in ./specofy/templates/plan-template.md it defines the structure of plan.md
run /plan blabla~~, it would create a bunch of files including plan.md under ./specify/specs/001-<branch name>, parallel to spec.md, as well as other css and html etc. files in root path.
Q: why there's no plan.md generated:
A: "The file was missing because the feature folder only contained the spec, so no plan artifact had been created yet. I’ve added it at plan.md." 2333
step 4:
/tasks
in speckit.tasks.agent.md file, it instructs the model to run `.specify/scripts/bash/setup-tasks.sh --json` which checks a few things in the current feature branch such as the planned 
documents paths inside the feature folder etc. And that script outputs those things to the terminal so the agent can use them for the rest of these instructions. It tells the agent to 
read those documents if they exist, then it has to generate tasks using the tasks template file which is inside the template folder. 
just run /tasks, tasks.md would be generated under ./specify/specs/001-<branch name>, parallel to spec.md and plan.md
step 4.1:
/speckit.analyze
it just takes a final glean over everything done so far. it is a strictly read only action.
just run /speckit.analyze, it would generate the analyze results in the copilot window
step 5:
/implement
Q: why didnt it generate /src:
A: plan.md didnt mention src/
OR
/speckit.tasks didn’t create real actionable tasks, implement has nothing to execute
OR 
wrong feature has been input: .specify/feature.json missing or empty

Q: why running /implement generates and edit more files than /speckit.implement:
A: /implement is a more autonomous, less constrained coding agent, while /speckit.implement strictly follows Spec Kit’s spec/plan/tasks and therefore produces a narrower, more controlled set of changes.


difference of agent.md and prompt.md:
agent.md: defines how AI behaves and executes tasks
prompt.md: a lightweight prompt template used as supporting context for the agent


open copilot window in VScode: ctrl+cmd+I
